<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-334-124  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 334 124.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lasers andamp; Optronics  June 1989 v8 n6 p32(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>From Lightwave Technologies, next-generation fibers. (From theLaboratories)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Weiss, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Lightwave Technologies is developing new optical-fibertechnologies and is capable of fabricating 5 percent of all theoptical fiber in the US.andP;  The company produces apolarization-preserving fiber with an elliptical monomode-diametercore and a pure silica monomode fiber.andP;  The monomode was developedin response to military specifications and is expected to beresistant to high radiation doses.andP;  It allows near-completerecovery of optical transmission at a gamma-ray dose of 2000 rads.andO;The company is focusing now on the production of high-strengthsilica fibers.andP;  Lightwave Technologies Chmn Frank Darby says hiscompany does not face a cash crisis, so common with smallcompanies, and is looking for increased usage for its ability toproduce 100 km of high-quality fiber per year.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lightwave Technologies (product development).andO;Topic:     Optoelectronic DevicesFiber OpticsLaser and Infrared CommunicationChemical Engineering.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablegraph.andO;Caption:   Specifications of Lightwave's rad-hard fiber. (table)Recovery time of Lightwave's rad-hard fiber. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>